--- title: "Welcome to PSYC 350 Laboratory" subtitle: "Lab 1" image: 'https://annotatedgilmoregirls.files.wordpress.com/2022/11/yale-university.jpg' author: "Instructor: Emma Marshall, JD, MA" from: markdown+emoji format: revealjs: logo: assets/logo.svg theme: assets/unl.scss menu: side: left slide-number: true date-format: long show-slide-number: all preview-links: true code-overflow: wrap incremental: true auto-animate: true transition: fade background-transition: fade transition-speed: fast footer: "Lab 1: Introduction to Psych 230 Lab" execute: echo: false --- ## Lab Instructor {background-image="images/fitz.png" background-opacity="0.2"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it - Emma Marshall, JD, MA - Law-Psychology (Joint JD/PhD) Program - Studies legal decision-making ::: ::: ::: incremental ::: ::: r-stack ![](images/searches.jpg){.fragment width="400" height="300"} ![](images/warrants.png){.fragment width="250" height="250"} ![](images/judges.png){.fragment width="250" height="250"} ::: ## Today's Tasks {background-image="images/fitz.png" background-opacity="0.1"} ::: body - Brief Introduction: The Purpose of Lab - Overview of where to find lab materials - Today's lab: - Introduction to final project data sets - Introduction to SPSS (OR JAMOVI) ::: ## Test Button ::: {.fragment fragment-index="1"}

For presentations sign-ups, you will have to pick a **date** to present on and an **article** to present.

:::
:::{.fragment fragment-index="2"}

So, who goes first? Let's let the button pick for us!


::: ::: ## Lab Information ::: panel-tabset ### Instructor **Lab instructor**: Emma Marshall J.D., M.A.
(But you can call me "Emma") - Email: emma.marshall\@husker.unl.edu - Office: [zoom](https://unl.zoom.us/j/6374970867) | Burnett 230 ::: callout-note If for some reason you need/want to find another TA's office hours see the main PSYCH 350 course page. ::: **Contact**: Emma Marshall - Email: emma.marshall@huskers.unl.edu - Office: [zoom](https://unl.zoom.us/j/6374970867) - Office hours: (TBD) Need to contact me by email? If you need to reach me outside of Lab, or have questions about anything, email is your best bet (emma.marshall@huskers.unl.edu). But please, please, PLEASE, include a clear subject header on your email so I know what it is about and can get back to you as quickly as possible. Other things to keep in mind: If you have a question about a specific assignment or issue--please include ALL the relevant information I need to locate what you are talking about. For example, if you have a question about Assignment 4 refer to it in your email as "Assignment 4" and not just "the assignment" I will generally do my best to get back to you within 24hrs of receiving your email (except for weekends). If you have not heard back from me, feel free to send another message! Chances are I didn't see your message and will appreciate the reminder! ### 155 Section **Meting time**: Tuesday, 10:00am -- 11:20am **Lab Room**: Burnett 233 ### 159 Section **Meting time**: Thursday, 1:00pm - 2:20pm **Lab Room**: Burnett 233 ::: ## Why is this course required? ![](images/p-value-statistics-meme.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it "Psych majors" vs. "Psych professionals" - ...distinction is about ability to **GENERATE** and **EVALUATE** new knowledge ::: ::: ::: columns ::: {.column width="50%"} ### ðŸ“‹ **Creating** Knowledge ![](images/scales.jpeg){.fragment .fade-up fig-align="center" width="307"} ::: ::: {.column width="50%"} ### ðŸ’­ :thought_balloon: **Evaluate** Knowledge ![](images/line.png){.fragment .fade-up fig-align="center" width="307"} ::: ::: ::: notes Possible Question- "Why is this course required???" The fundamental difference between "Psych majors" and "Psych professionals" is the ability to GENERATE and EVALUATE new knowledge To do your job, you'll have to know to find and evaluate knowledge that others have generated! You will sometimes have to generate new knowledge so you can do your job! ::: ## Empirical Research {.smaller .nonincremental} ![](images/anecdotes.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="200" height="70"} ::: inner-container ::: {.post-it .nonincremental} - Informs various **real world** decisions & processes - Peer-review & replication provide **credibility** - **Not** limited to academic psychology ::: ::: ::: {layout-ncol="3"} ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="2"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/find-jobs-on-newspaper-icon.svg){width="200"} ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="3"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/knowledge-icon.svg){width="175"} ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="4"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/direction-road-sign-icon.svg){width="200"} ::: ::: ::: notes The importance of empirical research is that it- - Informs every decision and action by professionals - Every decision and action made by psychological professionals is dependent upon research -- maybe their own, probably someone else's. - In order to be ethical (also legal and bill-able), each diagnosis, treatment choice, evaluation, and decision to stop treatment must be defended in terms of replicated, peer-reviewed, published research. - Not just clinical/treatment decisions but those made within areas of human resources, criminal justice, business, education, engineering, etc. -- all depend on, and use, knowledge acquired by psychological researchers. ::: ## ðŸ’­ :thought_balloon: Evaluating Knowledge {.smaller} ![](images/anecdotes.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="200" height="70"} ### **Everyone** needs to know how to ~~understand~~ empirical research ::: inner-container ::: post-it - **Competent** research consumers can: - :mag: **Find** relevant research - :clipboard: **Evaluate (& critique)** research quality (theory, methods, stats) - :dart: **Apply (& integrate)** valuable research information to own work ::: ::: ::: notes While not everyone needs to be a producer of empirical research, every psychological professional needs to be a competent consumer of research. Being a competent consumer of research means being able to ... - locate research that is relevant to your work - critique (evaluate) the quality of the research (theory, methodology, & stats) - integrate the useful information (that passes your evaluation) from the research into your own work ::: ## Example {.smaller} ![](images/anecdotes.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="200" height="70"} ::: columns ::: {.column width="40%"} ![](images/web_parent.png) ::: ::: {.column .incremental width="60%"} > "In the decade preceding the pandemic, the mean IQ score on standardized tests for children aged between three months and three years of age hovered around 100, but for children born during the pandemic that number tumbled to 78, according to the analysis, which is yet to be peer-reviewed." -Beth Morling, www.everydayresearchmethods.com ::: ::: ::: notes What might be some problems with this headline? Not peer reviewed. What about the pandemic might have changed the experiences and testing environment for babies? ::: ## :clipboard: Creating Knowledge {.smaller} ### Many jobs require research skills ::: inner-container ::: post-it - Funding sources, clients & employers look for: - :bar_chart: Evidence-based decision-making - :hourglass_flowing_sand: Efficiency and cost related concerns - :traffic_light: Competitive advantage ::: ::: ::: notes Most people (not just those in academia) find that they do need to produce research to do their jobs ... Why? Funding sources, clients, & bosses need evidence that what you are doing "works" and is "worth the expense". It is not enough that you "do it better" than the others. You need evidence that what you're doing works, and that it works better than your competitors. This evidence comes from research conducted, analyzed, and reported by you using your own patients/clients. ::: ## Creating Knowledge :clipboard: {.smaller} ### Research skills used in many industries ::: inner-container ::: post-it - People who understand the research process and can **evaluate**, **integrate**, and **apply** empirical have: - :money_with_wings: Better job prospects - :trophy: Improved job performance - :bookmark: More flexibility! ::: ::: ::: notes The point is...Research is going to be a more important part of your ongoing professional activities (and your successes) than you may realize. Professionals who better understand the research process and know how to evaluate, integrate, and apply the results from empirical research have greater employment potential do their jobs better! ::: ## :cold_sweat: Psychology is competitive {.smaller} ![](images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ### Positions often require **advanced** degrees ::: inner-container ::: post-it - Important skills for grad schools - Ex: UNL Psych Admissions ::: ::: ![](images/lawpsych.png){.fragment .absolute bottom="0" right="50" left="50" width="300" } ::: notes The psychological professions are competitive... for multiple reasons!!! - Many want jobs that "Helping people" is seen by many as an extension of their concerns for individuals and our society, so many want to become psychological professionals Positions for all of these are extremely competitive and required advanced degrees -- and those advanced degree programs are also extremely competitive... For example... Positions for all of these are extremely competitive and required advanced degrees -- some examples, each year ... Our graduate Clinical Psychology Program accepts 10-12 of the 200+ applicants Our Law-Psychology graduate program accepts 4-5 of 60 applicants The Educational Psychology Counseling program takes 6-8 of 100+ And within those programs -- the number of jobs available after also vary by industry and other factors. ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Clinical** Program accepts
10-12 of 200+ applicants ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Law-Psych** Program accepts
4-5 of 60 applicants ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Ed Psych** Program accepts
6-8 of 100+ applicants ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## So, what does this mean? {.smaller} ![](images/p-value-statistics-meme.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="70" height="70"} ### **Research** skills are ~~foundational~~ ::: inner-container ::: post-it - Schools (& employers) look for... - :bar_chart: Excellent performance in research methods/stats courses - :thought_balloon: Excellent performance in 400-level courses (writing & critical thinking skills) - :chart_with_upwards_trend: Research experience ::: ::: ::: notes So, we're here to pursue those activities together during your undergraduate "career" to increase your ability to compete for graduate school or a job. What do schools & employers look for ?? Excellent performance in research methods/stats courses Excellent performance in 400-level courses, especially writing and critical thinking skills (which can be improved using the knowledge and skills you'll have an opportunity to learn in here) Research experience (which will be easier to find if you do well in here and have the resultant skills) ::: ## Why is this course required? {.smaller} ![](images/p-value-statistics-meme.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="70" height="70"}

**Research** skills are at the heart of ~~ALL~~ psychological practice!

::: vspace ::: ::: columns ::: {.column .fragment width="50%"} #### **Creating** Knowledge ![](images/scales.jpeg){.absolute bottom="0" left="100" width="307"} ::: ::: {.column .fragment width="50%"} #### **Evaluate** Knowledge ![](images/line.png){.absolute bottom="0" right="100" width="307"} ::: :::
::: notes - Because research is at the heart of Psychological practice - Because the best way to get the education and training you need for your desired career is to master the procedures, techniques, skills, and tricks you will learn in this course. ::: ## Learning Objectives :dart: {.smaller} ::: inner-container ::: post-it - You will learn to... - :mag: **Locate, summarize, critique, & integrate** primary research and research reviews - :thought_balloon: **Propose** original research hypotheses based on your consideration of previous research - :clipboard: **Plan** the procedures & materials for data collection & analysis relevant to research hypotheses - :speech_balloon: **Report** all of the above using a standard (i.e., APA) format and style ::: ::: ::: notes - Every assignment done in this class tracks directly to knowledge and skills that will be expected to perform in 300/400-level classes FYI: advanced courses in this topic (Psyc 491/2) Useful skills you'll acquire in this course: Learn to locate, summarize, critique, and integrate primary research and research reviews Learn to propose original research hypotheses based on your consideration of previous research Learn to plan the procedures and materials for data collection and analysis relevant to research hypotheses Learn to report all of the above using a standard (i.e., APA) format and style ::: ## Keep in Mind :eyes: ::: vspace2 ::: ::: callout-warning - You need a "C" (not a "C-") for this course to count toward the Psychology Major - You **must** complete all exams to receive a passing grade in this course - You **must** complete all the take-home laboratory assignments to receive a passing grade in this class - You **must** attend lab classes to receive a passing grade in this class ::: ## Don't freak out! :full_moon_with_face: ::: r-stack ![](images/ahh.jpeg){.fragment width="615"} ![](images/documents.jpeg){.fragment width="578"} ::: # Questions? <script>
  // htmlwidgets need to know to resize themselves when slides are shown/hidden.
  // Fire the "slideenter" event (handled by htmlwidgets.js) when the current
  // slide changes (different for each slide format).
  (function () {
    // dispatch for htmlwidgets
    function fireSlideEnter() {
      const event = window.document.createEvent("Event");
      event.initEvent("slideenter", true, true);
      window.document.dispatchEvent(event);
    }

    function fireSlideChanged(previousSlide, currentSlide) {
      fireSlideEnter();

      // dispatch for shiny
      if (window.jQuery) {
        if (previousSlide) {
          window.jQuery(previousSlide).trigger("hidden");
        }
        if (currentSlide) {
          window.jQuery(currentSlide).trigger("shown");
        }
      }
    }

    // hookup for slidy
    if (window.w3c_slidy) {
      window.w3c_slidy.add_observer(function (slide_num) {
        // slide_num starts at position 1
        fireSlideChanged(null, w3c_slidy.slides[slide_num - 1]);
      });
    }

  })();
</script>
